{"cursor":"4562","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Ong Hok Ham' (1 May 1933 â 30 August 2007) was an eminent Chinese Indonesian\nhistorian considered one of the leading experts on Indonesian history during the\n19th century Dutch colonial rule. His particular area of knowledge centered on\nevents in Java during the period, and he authored a number of works dealing with\nthe subject.\n\nA native of Surabaya, East Java which, until the founding of Indonesia in\n1945, was a part of Dutch East Indies, Ong Hok Ham lived in the city of his\nbirth for the first twenty-five years of his life. In 1958, he moved to\nBandung, West Java, where he received his schooling and began his writing\ncareer. Seventeen years later, in 1975, he received his Ph.D in History from\nYale University with the dissertation The Residency of Madiun: Priyayi and\nPeasant in the Nineteenth Century.\n\nHe was a regular contributor to the Indonesian magazine Tempo and a collection\nof his pieces for the magazine written between 1976 and 2001, Wahyu yang Hilang,\nNegeri yang Guncang (A Lost Mandate, an Agitated Country) was published in 2002.\n\nHe wrote a series of other books, mostly a collection of essays and articles,\nincluding Runtuhnya Hindia Belanda (The Fall of the Netherlands Indies), Negara\ndan Rakyat (The State and the People), and Dari Soal Priayi sampai Nyi\nBlorongâRefleksi Historis Nusantara (From Priayi to Nyi BlorongâHistorical\nReflections on the Indonesian Archipelago).\n\nAn English-language collection of his writings, The Thugs, the Curtain Thief,\nand the Sugar Lord, received publication in 2003. The book chronicled power,\npolitics and culture in colonial Java.\n\nIn 1989, he retired from his duties as professor of history at the University of\nIndonesia. His final responsibility was as chairman of the Lembaga Studi Sejarah\nIndonesia (the Indonesian Institute of Historical Studies).\n\nOng Hok Ham, who was a Buddhist, suffered a stroke in 2001 and died six years\nlater at Dharmais Cancer Hospital in West Jakarta at the age of 74.\n","linknr":131,"url":"Ong_Hok_Ham","recorded":1375073173,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ong_Hok_Ham&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ong_Hok_Ham&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Chinese_name","/wiki/Chinese_surname","/wiki/Wang_(surname)","/wiki/Chinese_language","/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/Wade%E2%80%93Giles","#cite_note-Inside_Indonesia-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Chinese_Indonesians","/wiki/Indonesia","/wiki/Dutch_East_India_Company","/wiki/Java","/wiki/Surabaya","/wiki/East_Java","/wiki/Dutch_East_Indies","/wiki/Bandung","/wiki/West_Java","/wiki/Ph.D","/wiki/Yale_University","/wiki/Dissertation","/wiki/English_language","/wiki/University_of_Indonesia","/wiki/Buddhist","/wiki/West_Jakarta","/w/index.php?title=Ong_Hok_Ham&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/List_of_Chinese_Indonesians","/w/index.php?title=Ong_Hok_Ham&action=edit&section=2","#cite_ref-Inside_Indonesia_1-0","http://www.insideindonesia.org/content/view/1000/47/","#cite_ref-2","http://web.archive.org/web/20071022200703/http://thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20070831.A08","/wiki/The_Jakarta_Post","http://t